don dale alexander a nutrition specialist 
whose advice included a controversial 
codliveroilandorangejuicemixture for arthritis has died he 
was 70 
alexander died friday of heart complications at veterans 
administration hospital in los angeles 
he won acclaim in 1957 for his bestselling book arthritis 
and common sense and often appeared on television talk shows his 
treatments were described in life and other national magazines 
through study logic and common sense we have decided that 
arthritis is basically an oil deficiency in the human body and a 
lack of vitamin d alexander once wrote 
he recommended the cod liver oilorange juice mixture to achieve 
the proper level of vitamins and lubricating oils 
the federal trade commission accused alexander of making false 
and unsubstantiated claims an ftc examiner characterized 
alexanders claims as merely a hodgepodge of scientific folderol 
and medical mumbo jumbo 
the norwich conn native attended the norwich free academy and 
trinity college in connecticut and columbia university in new york 
