<TEXT>
tamil rebels shot and killed one 
soldier in a northern town sunday but the dayold ceasefire 
between government soldiers and insurgents held in other areas of 
the country officials said 
a second soldier died sunday of wounds inflicted in a saturday 
sniper attack 
the government blamed the rebels for several other ceasefire 
violations but said they could be due to lack of communications 
with remote places a spokesman for the rebels said the 
ceasefire appeared to be holding 
a joint governmentrebel delegation was scheduled to tour the 
ceasefire area tuesday the government said 
the tour was previously scheduled for monday and no reason was 
given for the postponement 
at least 376 people were killed in northern and eastern sri 
lanka since monday when tamil tiger rebels broke a 13monthold 
truce 
the death toll was compiled from accounts by witnesses military 
sources and rebel officials the government has acknowledged losing 
only 40 soldiers while the tigers admit only 72 guerrilla deaths 
the ceasefire went into effect at 6 pm saturday five days 
after the tigers besieged about 20 police stations and captured 
more than 850 policemen the government rushed reinforcements to 
the area and claimed to have retaken seven stations before the 
ceasefire 
there has been no word on the fate of the policemen but 
military sources and a lone survivor said 137 of the police were 
disarmed and massacred by rebels 
several ceasefire violations were reported saturday night and 
again on sunday but a government communique said reports 
indicate the ceasefire has been satisfactorily observed 
the soldier killed sunday was shot in vavuniya a town 135 miles 
northeast of colombo the communique said 
another soldier wounded by sniper fire saturday night near the 
port city of trincomalee 147 miles northeast of colombo died 
sunday it added 
residents in batticaloa and vavuniya said the ceasefire was 
generally holding but both the army and the tigers were on full 
alert 
the previous ceasefire that held for 13 months collapsed after 
fighting broke out in batticaloa a coastal town 136 miles 
northeast of colombo 
the batticaloa police station was the first captured by the 
tigers and is still in rebel hands 
ethnic tamil militants took up arms against the 
sinhalesedominated government in 1983 in their quest for a 
separate homeland 
the government and the tigers the most powerful tamil guerrilla 
group declared a ceasefire in may 1989 and started negotiations 
aimed at giving tamil greater autonomy 
more than 11000 people have been killed since the insurrection 
started 
tamils who make up 18 percent of sri lankas 16 million people 
are predominantly hindu and claim the sinhalese majority who are 
mostly buddhist discriminate against them in jobs and education 
sinhalese comprise 75 percent of the population 
