<TEXT>
on thanksgiving eve of 1984 randall robinson 
a black american walked into the south african embassy on 
massachusetts avenue in voice as smooth as worn saddle leather he 
chatted amiably for nearly an hour with thenambassador bernardus 
fourie when it was time to go he wouldnt 
not until he insisted south africa freed nelson mandela and 
all its black people 
that night in the dc jail robinson wondered where his first 
arrest for civil disobedience would lead america still was caught 
up in its own civil rights debate arguments raging over 
affirmative action and school busing the middle east central 
america eastern europe the cold war with the soviet union and the 
trade war with japan dominated its global concerns 
south africa was as far south on that list as it is on the map 
no more robinson now 48 is executive director of transafrica 
a lobbying group for black africa and this week he is bringing 
nelson mandela to the united states to ticker tape and yankee 
stadium in new york city to hollywood and the coliseum in los 
angeles to the oval office and congress in washington and to all 
the front pages in between 
and when he sends mandela home it will be with millions of 
dollars to replenish the cashstarved accounts of the african 
national congress to help it repatriate thousands of poor exiled 
members and reestablish internal operations after three decades of 
official banishment 
of greater import it will be with the assurance that this 
nation having lavished its affection on a man who strode so 
elegantly from his prison cell onto the international stage last 
february will not retreat from its economic sanctions against the 
south african government no matter how badly the bush 
administration might wish it so 
mandela 71 is coming to pick the fruits of political stardom 
just as lech walesa did a year ago the difference is that walesa 
the hero of eastern europes flood tide of democracy arrived the 
conquering hero mandela after nearly 28 years in prison is out 
of jail but he is not yet free said new york mayor david 
dinkins alluding to the south africa laws that still bar blacks 
from full voting privileges and the right to travel and live 
wherever they choose 
so mandela is sure to stir the special emotion that americans 
reserve for the heroic underdog that fondness is far less 
transitory than the cheers accorded victors though mandela may 
return one day in that role too 
robinson and other organizers of the mandela visit have set a 
34event 8city agenda that would gladden the heart and tax the 
energy of any rock star and any politician starting with the 
tickertape parade in manhattan on wednesday and ending with a 
rally at the oakland coliseum 10 days later 
other stops include boston atlanta miami detroit los angeles 
and washington where mandela will meet bush at the white house and 
address a joint session of congress something no black american 
has done 
mandela is likely to raise at least 8 million along the way 
from 5 general admission tickets at yankee stadium where 60000 
are expected to flock to 25000perplate dinners for corporate 
and showbusiness sympathizers a washington firm that manages the 
financial affairs of athletic superstars proserv expects to gross 
another 3 million from the sale of mandela tshirts posters 
coins souvenir mugs and other promotional items 
all of this said anc spokesman victor mashabela is 
powerful and positive 
and doubtlessly a little dismaying to the bush administration 
which will publicly embrace mandela as heartily as anyone but which 
would prefer that his american accolades for courage be shared with 
the man who released him south african president frederik w de 
klerk 
bushs predecessor ronald reagan unsuccessfully vetoed the 
1986 law that barred most trade with south africa bush has argued 
as did reagan that more american commerce would be a greater force 
for peaceful change than stiff sanctions 
recently the administration quietly suggested to key members of 
congress that sanctions be relaxed when pretoria meets the minimum 
conditions of the antiapartheid act particularly ending the 
national state of emergency and freeing all political prisoners 
earlier this month de klerk lifted the state of emergency in 
all but natal province but there are still south africans in 
prison for political reasons 
congressional leaders declared that it was too soon to consider 
easing sanctions and the administration backed down and the 
anticipated outpouring of public support for mandela during his 
us visit is sure to bolster congressional resolve on the issue 
mandela while effusive in his praise for de klerks gestures 
continues to insist that they should not be rewarded with any 
easing of us economic pressures that would be a grave 
mistake he said last week it would be regarded by the people 
of south africa as a stab in the back 
compounding any argument to the contrary by bush is the 
governments embarrassment over a recent report by the cox news 
service that the cia was responsible for mandelas capture 28 years 
ago having tipped the south african government to his whereabouts 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater initially declared we find 
no value in reviewing a 30yearold history in this case but his 
subsequent plea belied a greater sensitivity this happened 
during the john f kennedy administration dont beat me up 
for what the kennedy people did 
mandela a man of charity toward his aggrievers is not likely 
to rub that one in he wont need to he is coming a hero to 
americans known for viewing foreign leaders as either good guys or 
bad by the time he leaves it may be difficult for george bush or 
anyone else to persuade them to see the conflict between white and 
black south africa in shades of gray 
sometime later this summer de klerk too will come to 
washington he too will dine at the white house but he will not 
hear the roar of the american crowd the cheers that this week will 
belong to nelson mandela 
</TEXT>
