while russias popularly elected congress elected reformer boris 
n yeltsin president of the republic and declared sovereignty for 
the republic itself the republics party members seem to have 
little such independent feeling 
yet the same disputes over economic and social policies and the 
partys future that are tearing at national party unity will be 
present at the meeting of the 2700 russian communists 
russia with more than half of the soviet population and 
threequarters of its territory is home to 58 percent of the 
countrys more than 18 million communist party members 
but since the bolshevik revolution of 1917 russias identity 
largely has been submerged in the trappings of soviet socialism 
even though each of the other soviet republics has had its own 
party organization within the national party russia has not 
largely because russians had tended to dominate the national and 
republic communist parties 
its search for an identity has now taken it in the direction of 
founding its own communist party as well as in the direction of 
yeltsins more radical reforms 
conservatives radical reformers and the party leaders 
understand that the russian partys size makes it vital 
the 2700 party members from the russian republic are the same 
group that will represent it when the soviet communist party opens 
its 28th national congress on july 2 
the daily moskovsky komsomolets called this weeks conference a 
general rehearsal for the congress of 4700 party members from 
throughout the soviet union 
many party members and observers believe the national congress 
will result in the first split in the party since lenin 
at a meeting june 910 in leningrad some members called for 
gorbachev and his chief party adviser alexander n yakovlev to be 
thrown out of the party the daily komsomolskaya pravda reported 
thursday 
the leningrad group says it represents at least 15 million 
party members it has proposed its own platform and its own slate 
for the central committee 
gorbachevs communist party has to take responsibility for the 
results of perestroika viktor tyurkin a 39yearold leningrad 
party leader said in an interview it is not oriented to the 
majority of simple working people 
like several generations of communists before them tyurkin and 
his comrades believe that soviet socialism has protected working 
people from the whims of the market while reformers criticize 
gorbachevs economic program for timidity in a time of crisis the 
leningrad group sees in them a breach of faith 
despite the leningrad groups criticism of gorbachev there is a 
strong possibility that it will form an alliance with the national 
party leadership at the conference said vladimir lysenko a leader 
of the reformminded democratic platform 
a few months ago gorbachev spoke out against the founding of 
the russian party before the national party congress but he now 
favors it lysenko told the moskovsky komsomolets newspaper the 
leningrad group also favors it 
representatives of the leningrad meetings have been invited to 
help write the conference documents but no members of democratic 
platform have been invited lysenko said 
democratic platform is preparing its own set of documents that 
its small group of delegates will present at the conference he 
said 
vladimir komarov a spokesman for the leningrad group said it 
will have at least 25 delegates to the national conference members 
of the democratic platform say they expect to have a small group as 
well 
soviet party leaders have given no indication so far what 
direction they think the party should take 
vyacheslav shostakovsky another democratic platform leader 
said that even though organizers of the leningrad meetings do not 
have any influential nationwide leaders they can reach a large 
number of russians frustrated by the failures of reform 
by such appeals a bloc can be formed that can create a rather 
potent threat to political stability he said 
</TEXT>
