<TEXT>
oileating microbes spread over part of 
an oil slick from the supertanker mega borg appear to have done 
their job but officials said they launched another experiment 
sunday to make sure 
on friday about 100 pounds of hungry bacteria were spread over 
an acre of the slick from the crippled norwegian tanker that 
exploded june 8 in the gulf of mexico 
it was the first use of the process called bioremediation on 
open waters 
a flyover sunday of the area marked by a buoy showed little oil 
in the treated waters state officials said 
there certainly wasnt any oil over there said texas water 
commission chairman bj buck wynne 
however wynne said it could not be determined if the oil was 
removed by the microbes or currents or whether the buoy had moved 
visually it appeared there was hardly anything left it 
appears degradation of the oil has occurred said blanton moore 
of the texas general land office 
moore said officials wont know for certain from the first 
application so they started another experiment sunday by 
encircling two areas of the slick with booms each 15 feet in 
diameter 
officials plan to spread microbes on one area but do nothing 
with the other moore said water samples will be taken from both 
areas and results should be available early in the week 
carl oppenheimer a university of texas microbiologist who has 
been working on bioremediation for 15 years has predicted the 
experiment will succeed and show that the process should be used on 
a wider scale in oil spills 
bioremediation uses naturally occurring bacteria to break down 
oil into harmless fatty acids eaten by marine life 
